The fusion operation $ \oplus $ is defined in Equation (16) as:

$$
\mathcal{D} \oplus \mathcal{D}' = \bigcup_{d' \in \mathcal{D}'} (\mathcal{D} \oplus d')
$$

And the per-detection fusion rule in Equation (17) is:

$$
\mathcal{D} \oplus d_{\text{new}} =
\begin{cases}
\mathcal{D} \cup \{d_{\text{new}}\} & \text{if } \forall d_{\text{exist}} \in \mathcal{D}, \neg \phi(d_{\text{new}}, d_{\text{exist}}) \\
\mathcal{D} \setminus d_{\text{exist}} \cup \mathcal{F}(d_{\text{new}}, d_{\text{exist}}) & \text{if } \exists d_{\text{exist}} \in \mathcal{D}, \phi(d_{\text{new}}, d_{\text{exist}})
\end{cases}
$$

This indicates that if a new detection does not overlap with any existing detection, it is simply added. If there is overlap, the existing detection is removed and replaced with the fused result. This is a form of merging, not simple addition or replacement.

Looking at the options:

A. The new retained detections are added to the existing detections without any modification. → Incorrect, because overlap leads to fusion, not simple addition.

B. The existing detections are replaced entirely by the new retained detections. → Incorrect, because existing detections are either kept (if no overlap) or fused (if overlap).

C. The new retained detections are merged with the existing detections using a symmetric difference operation. → Incorrect, because symmetric difference would remove overlapping elements, but here overlapping elements are fused, not removed.

D. The new retained detections are filtered based on the existing detections before being added. → Correct, because the fusion operation checks for overlaps and either adds or fuses detections based on whether they overlap with existing ones.

Thus, the correct answer is D.

