From the retrieved page, Equation (15) defines the mean pairwise overlap as:

$$
M_{\text{iou\_overlap}} = \frac{1}{N_{\text{pairs}}} \sum_{p<q} \text{IoU}(B_p, B_q)
$$

where $ N_{\text{pairs}} = \binom{N_{\text{bboxes}}}{2} $, which is the number of unordered pairs of bounding boxes. This means that as the number of bounding boxes ($ N_{\text{bboxes}} $) increases, the denominator $ N_{\text{pairs}} $ grows quadratically (i.e., $ N_{\text{bboxes}}^2 $).

The numerator is the sum of IoU values over all pairs. While more bounding boxes can lead to more overlapping pairs, the mean is computed by dividing the total sum by the number of pairs. Therefore, if the distribution of IoU values remains consistent, increasing the number of boxes would not inherently increase the mean — it would simply average over more pairs. However, if the additional boxes tend to have lower IoU values (e.g., due to increased crowding or occlusion), the mean could decrease.

But critically, the formula includes normalization by the number of pairs, which is explicitly stated in the definition. This normalization ensures that the mean is not biased by the sheer number of pairs. Thus, the mean pairwise overlap is a normalized value that reflects the average overlap per pair, independent of the total count of bounding boxes.

This supports option C: “It remains constant because the formula normalizes by the number of pairs.”

<answer>C. It remains constant because the formula normalizes by the number of pairs.</answer>
